  69 # This is the default internal TF session used by Keras.
  70 # It can be set manually via `set_session(sess)`.
  71 _SESSION = None

  73 # This dictionary holds a mapping {graph: learning_phase}.
  74 # A learning phase is a bool tensor used to run Keras models in
  75 # either train mode (learning_phase == 1) or test mode (learning_phase == 0).
  76 _GRAPH_LEARNING_PHASES = weakref.WeakKeyDictionary()
  77 
  78 
  79 # _DUMMY_EAGER_GRAPH is used as a key in _GRAPH_LEARNING_PHASES.
  80 # We keep a separate reference to it to make sure it does not get removed from
  81 # _GRAPH_LEARNING_PHASES. We use a dummy class instead of something like a
  82 # string because strings are not weakly-referencable.
  83 class _DummyEagerGraph(object):
  84   pass
  85 _DUMMY_EAGER_GRAPH = _DummyEagerGraph()
  86 
  87 # This boolean flag can be set to True to leave variable initialization
  88 # up to the user.
  89 # Change its value via `manual_variable_initialization(value)`.
  90 _MANUAL_VAR_INIT = False

 278 # A global dictionary mapping graph objects to an index of counters used
 279 # for various layer names in each graph.
 280 # Allows to give unique autogenerated names to layers, in a graph-specific way.
 281 PER_GRAPH_LAYER_NAME_UIDS = weakref.WeakKeyDictionary()
 282 
 283 
 284 @tf_export('keras.backend.get_uid')
 285 def get_uid(prefix=''):
 286   """Associates a string prefix with an integer counter in a TensorFlow graph.
 287 
 288   Arguments:
 289     prefix: String prefix to index.
 290 
 291   Returns:
 292     Unique integer ID.
 293 
 294   Example:
 295 
 296   ```
 297     >>> get_uid('dense')
 298     1
 299     >>> get_uid('dense')
 300     2
 301   ```
 302   """
 303   graph = ops.get_default_graph()
 304   if graph not in PER_GRAPH_LAYER_NAME_UIDS:
 305     PER_GRAPH_LAYER_NAME_UIDS[graph] = collections.defaultdict(int)
 306   layer_name_uids = PER_GRAPH_LAYER_NAME_UIDS[graph]
 307   layer_name_uids[prefix] += 1
 308   return layer_name_uids[prefix]
 309 
 310 
 311 @tf_export('keras.backend.reset_uids')
 312 def reset_uids():
 313   """Resets graph identifiers.
 314   """
 315   per_graph_layer_name_uids = PER_GRAPH_LAYER_NAME_UIDS
 316   keys = list(per_graph_layer_name_uids.keys())
 317   for key in keys:
 318     del per_graph_layer_name_uids[key]

 321 @tf_export('keras.backend.clear_session')
 322 def clear_session():
 323   """Destroys the current TF graph and creates a new one.
 324 
 325   Useful to avoid clutter from old models / layers.
 326   """
 327   global _SESSION
 328   global _GRAPH_LEARNING_PHASES  # pylint: disable=global-variable-not-assigned
 329   global _GRAPH_VARIABLES  # pylint: disable=global-variable-not-assigned
 330   global _GRAPH_TF_OPTIMIZERS  # pylint: disable=global-variable-not-assigned
 331   ops.reset_default_graph()
 332   reset_uids()
 333   _SESSION = None
 334   phase = array_ops.placeholder_with_default(
 335       False, shape=(), name='keras_learning_phase')
 336   _GRAPH_LEARNING_PHASES = {}
 337   _GRAPH_LEARNING_PHASES[ops.get_default_graph()] = phase
 338   _GRAPH_VARIABLES.pop(ops.get_default_graph(), None)
 339   _GRAPH_TF_OPTIMIZERS.pop(ops.get_default_graph(), None)
 340

 342 @tf_export('keras.backend.manual_variable_initialization')
 343 def manual_variable_initialization(value):
 344   """Sets the manual variable initialization flag.
 345 
 346   This boolean flag determines whether
 347   variables should be initialized
 348   as they are instantiated (default), or if
 349   the user should handle the initialization
 350   (e.g. via `tf.initialize_all_variables()`).
 351 
 352   Arguments:
 353       value: Python boolean.
 354   """
 355   global _MANUAL_VAR_INIT
 356   _MANUAL_VAR_INIT = value
 357

 359 @tf_export('keras.backend.learning_phase')
 360 def learning_phase():
 361   """Returns the learning phase flag.
 362 
 363   The learning phase flag is a bool tensor (0 = test, 1 = train)
 364   to be passed as input to any Keras function
 365   that uses a different behavior at train time and test time.
 366 
 367   Returns:
 368       Learning phase (scalar integer tensor or Python integer).
 369   """
 370   with ops.init_scope():
 371     # We always check & set the learning phase inside the init_scope,
 372     # otherwise the wrong default_graph will be used to look up the learning
 373     # phase inside of functions & defuns.
 374     #
 375     # This is because functions & defuns (both in graph & in eager mode)
 376     # will always execute non-eagerly using a function-specific default
 377     # subgraph.
 378     if context.executing_eagerly():
 379       if _DUMMY_EAGER_GRAPH not in _GRAPH_LEARNING_PHASES:
 380         # Fallback to inference mode as default.
 381         return 0
 382       return _GRAPH_LEARNING_PHASES[_DUMMY_EAGER_GRAPH]
 383 
 384     graph = ops.get_default_graph()
 385     if graph not in _GRAPH_LEARNING_PHASES:
 386       phase = array_ops.placeholder_with_default(
 387           False, shape=(), name='keras_learning_phase')
 388       _GRAPH_LEARNING_PHASES[graph] = phase
 389     return _GRAPH_LEARNING_PHASES[graph]
 390 
 391 
 392 @tf_export('keras.backend.set_learning_phase')
 393 def set_learning_phase(value):
 394   """Sets the learning phase to a fixed value.
 395 
 396   Arguments:
 397       value: Learning phase value, either 0 or 1 (integers).
 398 
 399   Raises:
 400       ValueError: if `value` is neither `0` nor `1`.
 401   """
 402   global _GRAPH_LEARNING_PHASES  # pylint: disable=global-variable-not-assigned
 403   if value not in {0, 1}:
 404     raise ValueError('Expected learning phase to be 0 or 1.')
 405   with ops.init_scope():
 406     if context.executing_eagerly():
 407       _GRAPH_LEARNING_PHASES[_DUMMY_EAGER_GRAPH] = value
 408     else:
 409       _GRAPH_LEARNING_PHASES[ops.get_default_graph()] = value
 410 
 411 
 412 @tf_contextlib.contextmanager
 413 def learning_phase_scope(value):
 414   """Provides a scope within which the learning phase is equal to `value`.
 415 
 416   The learning phase gets restored to its original value upon exiting the scope.
 417 
 418   Arguments:
 419      value: Learning phase value, either 0 or 1 (integers).
 420 
 421   Yields:
 422     The provided value.
 423 
 424   Raises:
 425      ValueError: if `value` is neither `0` nor `1`.
 426   """
 427   if value not in {0, 1}:
 428     raise ValueError('Expected learning phase to be 0 or 1.')
 429   previous_value = learning_phase()
 430   try:
 431     set_learning_phase(value)
 432     yield value
 433   finally:
 434     # Restore learning phase to initial value.
 435     with ops.init_scope():
 436       if context.executing_eagerly():
 437         _GRAPH_LEARNING_PHASES[_DUMMY_EAGER_GRAPH] = previous_value
 438       else:
 439         _GRAPH_LEARNING_PHASES[ops.get_default_graph()] = previous_value
 440

 442 @tf_export('keras.backend.get_session')
 443 def get_session():
 444   """Returns the TF session to be used by the backend.
 445 
 446   If a default TensorFlow session is available, we will return it.
 447 
 448   Else, we will return the global Keras session.
 449 
 450   If no global Keras session exists at this point:
 451   we will create a new global session.
 452 
 453   Note that you can manually set the global session
 454   via `K.set_session(sess)`.
 455 
 456   Returns:
 457       A TensorFlow session.
 458   """
 459   global _SESSION
 460   default_session = ops.get_default_session()
 461   if default_session is not None:
 462     session = default_session
 463   else:
 464     if _SESSION is None:
 465       _SESSION = session_module.Session(config=get_default_session_config())
 466     session = _SESSION
 467   if not _MANUAL_VAR_INIT:
 468     with session.graph.as_default():
 469       _initialize_variables(session)
 470   return session
 471 
 472 
 473 @tf_export('keras.backend.set_session')
 474 def set_session(session):
 475   """Sets the global TensorFlow session.
 476 
 477   Arguments:
 478       session: A TF Session.
 479   """
 480   global _SESSION
 481   _SESSION = session
 482

 484 def get_default_session_config():
 485   if not os.environ.get('OMP_NUM_THREADS'):
 486     config = config_pb2.ConfigProto(allow_soft_placement=True)
 487   else:
 488     num_thread = int(os.environ.get('OMP_NUM_THREADS'))
 489     config = config_pb2.ConfigProto(
 490         intra_op_parallelism_threads=num_thread, allow_soft_placement=True)
 491   return config

 497 class _TfDeviceCaptureOp(object):
 498   """Class for capturing the TF device scope."""
 499 
 500   def __init__(self):
 501     self.device = None
 502 
 503   def _set_device(self, device):
 504     """This method captures TF's explicit device scope setting."""
 505     self.device = device
 506 
 507 
 508 def _get_current_tf_device():
 509   """Return explicit device of current context, otherwise returns `None`.
 510 
 511   Returns:
 512       If the current device scope is explicitly set, it returns a string with
 513       the device (`CPU` or `GPU`). If the scope is not explicitly set, it will
 514       return `None`.
 515   """
 516   g = ops.get_default_graph()
 517   op = _TfDeviceCaptureOp()
 518   g._apply_device_functions(op)
 519   return op.device
 520 
 521 
 522 def _is_current_explicit_device(device_type):
 523   """Check if the current device is explicitly set on the device type specified.
 524 
 525   Arguments:
 526       device_type: A string containing `GPU` or `CPU` (case-insensitive).
 527 
 528   Returns:
 529       A boolean indicating if the current device scope is explicitly set on the
 530       device type.
 531 
 532   Raises:
 533       ValueError: If the `device_type` string indicates an unsupported device.
 534   """
 535   device_type = device_type.upper()
 536   if device_type not in ['CPU', 'GPU']:
 537     raise ValueError('`device_type` should be either "CPU" or "GPU".')
 538   device = _get_current_tf_device()
 539   return device is not None and device.device_type == device_type.upper()
 540 
 541 
 542 def _get_available_gpus():
 543   """Get a list of available gpu devices (formatted as strings).
 544 
 545   Returns:
 546       A list of available GPU devices.
 547   """
 548   global _LOCAL_DEVICES
 549   if _LOCAL_DEVICES is None:
 550     _LOCAL_DEVICES = get_session().list_devices()
 551   return [x.name for x in _LOCAL_DEVICES if x.device_type == 'GPU']
 552 
 553 
 554 def _has_nchw_support():
 555   """Check whether the current scope supports NCHW ops.
 556 
 557   TensorFlow does not support NCHW on CPU. Therefore we check if we are not
 558   explicitly put on
 559   CPU, and have GPUs available. In this case there will be soft-placing on the
 560   GPU device.
 561 
 562   Returns:
 563       bool: if the current scope device placement would support nchw
 564   """
 565   explicitly_on_cpu = _is_current_explicit_device('CPU')
 566   gpus_available = bool(_get_available_gpus())
 567   return not explicitly_on_cpu and gpus_available

 586 @tf_export('keras.backend.is_sparse')
 587 def is_sparse(tensor):
 588   """Returns whether a tensor is a sparse tensor.
 589 
 590   Arguments:
 591       tensor: A tensor instance.
 592 
 593   Returns:
 594       A boolean.
 595 
 596   Example:
 597   ```python
 598       >>> from keras import backend as K
 599       >>> a = K.placeholder((2, 2), sparse=False)
 600       >>> print(K.is_sparse(a))
 601       False
 602       >>> b = K.placeholder((2, 2), sparse=True)
 603       >>> print(K.is_sparse(b))
 604       True
 605   ```
 606   """
 607   return isinstance(tensor, sparse_tensor.SparseTensor)

 610 @tf_export('keras.backend.to_dense')
 611 def to_dense(tensor):
 612   """Converts a sparse tensor into a dense tensor and returns it.
 613 
 614   Arguments:
 615       tensor: A tensor instance (potentially sparse).
 616 
 617   Returns:
 618       A dense tensor.
 619 
 620   Examples:
 621   ```python
 622       >>> from keras import backend as K
 623       >>> b = K.placeholder((2, 2), sparse=True)
 624       >>> print(K.is_sparse(b))
 625       True
 626       >>> c = K.to_dense(b)
 627       >>> print(K.is_sparse(c))
 628       False
 629   ```
 630   """
 631   if is_sparse(tensor):
 632     return sparse_ops.sparse_tensor_to_dense(tensor)
 633   else:
 634     return tensor

 640 @tf_export('keras.backend.variable')
 641 def variable(value, dtype=None, name=None, constraint=None):
 642   """Instantiates a variable and returns it.
 643 
 644   Arguments:
 645       value: Numpy array, initial value of the tensor.
 646       dtype: Tensor type.
 647       name: Optional name string for the tensor.
 648       constraint: Optional projection function to be
 649           applied to the variable after an optimizer update.
 650 
 651   Returns:
 652       A variable instance (with Keras metadata included).
 653 
 654   Examples:
 655   ```python
 656       >>> from keras import backend as K
 657       >>> val = np.array([[1, 2], [3, 4]])
 658       >>> kvar = K.variable(value=val, dtype='float64', name='example_var')
 659       >>> K.dtype(kvar)
 660       'float64'
 661       >>> print(kvar)
 662       example_var
 663       >>> kvar.eval()
 664       array([[ 1.,  2.],
 665              [ 3.,  4.]])
 666   ```
 667   """
 668   if dtype is None:
 669     dtype = floatx()
 670   if hasattr(value, 'tocoo'):
 671     sparse_coo = value.tocoo()
 672     indices = np.concatenate((np.expand_dims(sparse_coo.row, 1), np.expand_dims(
 673         sparse_coo.col, 1)), 1)
 674     v = sparse_tensor.SparseTensor(
 675         indices=indices, values=sparse_coo.data, dense_shape=sparse_coo.shape)
 676     v._keras_shape = sparse_coo.shape
 677     v._uses_learning_phase = False
 678     return v
 679   v = resource_variable_ops.ResourceVariable(
 680       value,
 681       dtype=dtypes_module.as_dtype(dtype),
 682       name=name,
 683       constraint=constraint)
 684   if isinstance(value, np.ndarray):
 685     v._keras_shape = value.shape
 686   elif hasattr(value, 'shape'):
 687     v._keras_shape = int_shape(value)
 688   v._uses_learning_phase = False
 689   track_variable(v)
 690   return v
 691 
 692 
 693 def track_tf_optimizer(tf_optimizer):
 694   """Tracks the given TF optimizer for initialization of its variables."""
 695   if context.executing_eagerly():
 696     return
 697   graph = ops.get_default_graph()
 698   optimizers = _GRAPH_TF_OPTIMIZERS.setdefault(graph, weakref.WeakSet())
 699   optimizers.add(tf_optimizer)
 700 
 701 def track_variable(v):
 702   """Tracks the given variable for initialization."""
 703   if context.executing_eagerly():
 704     return
 705   graph = v.graph if hasattr(v, 'graph') else ops.get_default_graph()
 706   if graph not in _GRAPH_VARIABLES:
 707     _GRAPH_VARIABLES[graph] = weakref.WeakSet()
 708   _GRAPH_VARIABLES[graph].add(v)
 709 
 710 
 711 def _get_variables(graph=None):
 712   """Returns variables corresponding to the given graph for initialization."""
 713   assert not context.executing_eagerly()
 714   variables = _GRAPH_VARIABLES.setdefault(graph, weakref.WeakSet())
 715   for opt in _GRAPH_TF_OPTIMIZERS.get(graph, set()):
 716     variables.update(opt.optimizer.variables())
 717   return variables
 718 
 719 
 720 def _initialize_variables(session):
 721   """Utility to initialize uninitialized variables on the fly."""
 722   variables = _get_variables(ops.get_default_graph())
 723   candidate_vars = []
 724   for v in variables:
 725     if not getattr(v, '_keras_initialized', False):
 726       candidate_vars.append(v)
 727   if candidate_vars:
 728     # This step is expensive, so we only run it on variables not already
 729     # marked as initialized.
 730     is_initialized = session.run(
 731         [variables_module.is_variable_initialized(v) for v in candidate_vars])
 732     uninitialized_vars = []
 733     for flag, v in zip(is_initialized, candidate_vars):
 734       if not flag:
 735         uninitialized_vars.append(v)
 736       v._keras_initialized = True
 737     if uninitialized_vars:
 738       session.run(variables_module.variables_initializer(uninitialized_vars))
 739

 759 def is_keras_tensor(x):
 760   """Returns whether `x` is a Keras tensor.
 761 
 762   A "Keras tensor" is a tensor that was returned by a Keras layer,
 763   (`Layer` class) or by `Input`.
 764 
 765   Arguments:
 766       x: A candidate tensor.
 767 
 768   Returns:
 769       A boolean: Whether the argument is a Keras tensor.
 770 
 771   Raises:
 772       ValueError: In case `x` is not a symbolic tensor.
 773 
 774   Examples:
 775   ```python
 776       >>> from keras import backend as K
 777       >>> from keras.layers import Input, Dense
 778       >>> np_var = numpy.array([1, 2])
 779       >>> K.is_keras_tensor(np_var) # A numpy array is not a symbolic tensor.
 780       ValueError
 781       >>> k_var = tf.placeholder('float32', shape=(1,1))
 782       >>> K.is_keras_tensor(k_var) # A variable indirectly created outside of
 783       keras is not a Keras tensor.
 784       False
 785       >>> keras_var = K.variable(np_var)
 786       >>> K.is_keras_tensor(keras_var)  # A variable created with the keras
 787       backend is not a Keras tensor.
 788       False
 789       >>> keras_placeholder = K.placeholder(shape=(2, 4, 5))
 790       >>> K.is_keras_tensor(keras_placeholder)  # A placeholder is not a Keras
 791       tensor.
 792       False
 793       >>> keras_input = Input([10])
 794       >>> K.is_keras_tensor(keras_input) # An Input is a Keras tensor.
 795       True
 796       >>> keras_layer_output = Dense(10)(keras_input)
 797       >>> K.is_keras_tensor(keras_layer_output) # Any Keras layer output is a
 798       Keras tensor.
 799       True
 800   ```
 801   """
 802   if (not isinstance(x, (ops.Tensor,
 803                          variables_module.Variable,
 804                          sparse_tensor.SparseTensor)) and
 805       x.__class__.__name__ != 'DeferredTensor'):
 806     raise ValueError('Unexpectedly found an instance of type `' + str(type(x)) +
 807                      '`. Expected a symbolic tensor instance.')
 808   return hasattr(x, '_keras_history')

 811 @tf_export('keras.backend.placeholder')
 812 def placeholder(shape=None, ndim=None, dtype=None, sparse=False, name=None):
 813   """Instantiates a placeholder tensor and returns it.
 814 
 815   Arguments:
 816       shape: Shape of the placeholder
 817           (integer tuple, may include `None` entries).
 818       ndim: Number of axes of the tensor.
 819           At least one of {`shape`, `ndim`} must be specified.
 820           If both are specified, `shape` is used.

 826       Tensor instance (with Keras metadata included).
 827

 829   ```python
 830       >>> from keras import backend as K

 834   ```

 836   if dtype is None:
 837     dtype = floatx()

 839     if ndim:
 840       shape = tuple([None for _ in range(ndim)])

 843   else:
 844     x = array_ops.placeholder(dtype, shape=shape, name=name)

 846   return x

1364 @tf_export('keras.backend.dot')
1365 def dot(x, y):
1366   """Multiplies 2 tensors (and/or variables) and returns a *tensor*.
1367 
1368   When attempting to multiply a nD tensor
1369   with a nD tensor, it reproduces the Theano behavior.
1370   (e.g. `(2, 3) * (4, 3, 5) -> (2, 4, 5)`)
1371 
1372   Arguments:
1373       x: Tensor or variable.
1374       y: Tensor or variable.
1375 
1376   Returns:
1377       A tensor, dot product of `x` and `y`.
1378 
1379   Examples:
1380   ```python
1381       # dot product between tensors
1382       >>> x = K.placeholder(shape=(2, 3))
1383       >>> y = K.placeholder(shape=(3, 4))
1384       >>> xy = K.dot(x, y)
1385       >>> xy
1386       <tf.Tensor 'MatMul_9:0' shape=(2, 4) dtype=float32>
1387   ```
1388 
1389   ```python
1390       # dot product between tensors
1391       >>> x = K.placeholder(shape=(32, 28, 3))
1392       >>> y = K.placeholder(shape=(3, 4))
1393       >>> xy = K.dot(x, y)
1394       >>> xy
1395       <tf.Tensor 'MatMul_9:0' shape=(32, 28, 4) dtype=float32>
1396   ```
1397 
1398   ```python
1399       # Theano-like behavior example
1400       >>> x = K.random_uniform_variable(shape=(2, 3), low=0, high=1)
1401       >>> y = K.ones((4, 3, 5))
1402       >>> xy = K.dot(x, y)
1403       >>> K.int_shape(xy)
1404       (2, 4, 5)
1405   ```
1406   """
1407   if ndim(x) is not None and (ndim(x) > 2 or ndim(y) > 2):
1408     x_shape = []
1409     for i, s in zip(int_shape(x), array_ops.unstack(array_ops.shape(x))):
1410       if i is not None:
1411         x_shape.append(i)
1412       else:
1413         x_shape.append(s)
1414     x_shape = tuple(x_shape)
1415     y_shape = []
1416     for i, s in zip(int_shape(y), array_ops.unstack(array_ops.shape(y))):
1417       if i is not None:
1418         y_shape.append(i)
1419       else:
1420         y_shape.append(s)
1421     y_shape = tuple(y_shape)
1422     y_permute_dim = list(range(ndim(y)))
1423     y_permute_dim = [y_permute_dim.pop(-2)] + y_permute_dim
1424     xt = array_ops.reshape(x, [-1, x_shape[-1]])
1425     yt = array_ops.reshape(
1426         array_ops.transpose(y, perm=y_permute_dim), [y_shape[-2], -1])
1427     return array_ops.reshape(
1428         math_ops.matmul(xt, yt), x_shape[:-1] + y_shape[:-2] + y_shape[-1:])
1429   if is_sparse(x):
1430     out = sparse_ops.sparse_tensor_dense_matmul(x, y)
1431   else:
1432     out = math_ops.matmul(x, y)
1433   return out
1434

1436 @tf_export('keras.backend.batch_dot')
1437 def batch_dot(x, y, axes=None):
1438   """Batchwise dot product.
1439 
1440   `batch_dot` is used to compute dot product of `x` and `y` when
1441   `x` and `y` are data in batch, i.e. in a shape of
1442   `(batch_size, :)`.
1443   `batch_dot` results in a tensor or variable with less dimensions
1444   than the input. If the number of dimensions is reduced to 1,
1445   we use `expand_dims` to make sure that ndim is at least 2.
1446 
1447   Arguments:
1448       x: Keras tensor or variable with `ndim >= 2`.
1449       y: Keras tensor or variable with `ndim >= 2`.
1450       axes: list of (or single) int with target dimensions.
1451           The lengths of `axes[0]` and `axes[1]` should be the same.
1452 
1453   Returns:
1454       A tensor with shape equal to the concatenation of `x`'s shape
1455       (less the dimension that was summed over) and `y`'s shape
1456       (less the batch dimension and the dimension that was summed over).
1457       If the final rank is 1, we reshape it to `(batch_size, 1)`.
1458 
1459   Examples:
1460       Assume `x = [[1, 2], [3, 4]]` and `y = [[5, 6], [7, 8]]`
1461       `batch_dot(x, y, axes=1) = [[17, 53]]` which is the main diagonal
1462       of `x.dot(y.T)`, although we never have to calculate the off-diagonal
1463       elements.
1464 
1465       Shape inference:
1466       Let `x`'s shape be `(100, 20)` and `y`'s shape be `(100, 30, 20)`.
1467       If `axes` is (1, 2), to find the output shape of resultant tensor,
1468           loop through each dimension in `x`'s shape and `y`'s shape:
1469 
1470       * `x.shape[0]` : 100 : append to output shape
1471       * `x.shape[1]` : 20 : do not append to output shape,
1472           dimension 1 of `x` has been summed over. (`dot_axes[0]` = 1)
1473       * `y.shape[0]` : 100 : do not append to output shape,
1474           always ignore first dimension of `y`
1475       * `y.shape[1]` : 30 : append to output shape
1476       * `y.shape[2]` : 20 : do not append to output shape,
1477           dimension 2 of `y` has been summed over. (`dot_axes[1]` = 2)
1478       `output_shape` = `(100, 30)`
1479 
1480   ```python
1481       >>> x_batch = K.ones(shape=(32, 20, 1))
1482       >>> y_batch = K.ones(shape=(32, 30, 20))
1483       >>> xy_batch_dot = K.batch_dot(x_batch, y_batch, axes=[1, 2])
1484       >>> K.int_shape(xy_batch_dot)
1485       (32, 1, 30)
1486   ```
1487   """
1488   if isinstance(axes, int):
1489     axes = (axes, axes)
1490   x_ndim = ndim(x)
1491   y_ndim = ndim(y)
1492   if axes is None:
1493     # behaves like tf.batch_matmul as default
1494     axes = [x_ndim - 1, y_ndim - 2]
1495   if x_ndim > y_ndim:
1496     diff = x_ndim - y_ndim
1497     y = array_ops.reshape(y,
1498                           array_ops.concat(
1499                               [array_ops.shape(y), [1] * (diff)], axis=0))
1500   elif y_ndim > x_ndim:
1501     diff = y_ndim - x_ndim
1502     x = array_ops.reshape(x,
1503                           array_ops.concat(
1504                               [array_ops.shape(x), [1] * (diff)], axis=0))
1505   else:
1506     diff = 0
1507   if ndim(x) == 2 and ndim(y) == 2:
1508     if axes[0] == axes[1]:
1509       out = math_ops.reduce_sum(math_ops.multiply(x, y), axes[0])
1510     else:
1511       out = math_ops.reduce_sum(
1512           math_ops.multiply(array_ops.transpose(x, [1, 0]), y), axes[1])
1513   else:
1514     adj_x = None if axes[0] == ndim(x) - 1 else True
1515     adj_y = True if axes[1] == ndim(y) - 1 else None
1516     out = math_ops.matmul(x, y, adjoint_a=adj_x, adjoint_b=adj_y)
1517   if diff:
1518     if x_ndim > y_ndim:
1519       idx = x_ndim + y_ndim - 3
1520     else:
1521       idx = x_ndim - 1
1522     out = array_ops.squeeze(out, list(range(idx, idx + diff)))
1523   if ndim(out) == 1:
1524     out = expand_dims(out, 1)
1525   return out
1526

2090 def _regular_normalize_batch_in_training(x,
2091                                          gamma,
2092                                          beta,
2093                                          reduction_axes,
2094                                          epsilon=1e-3):
2095   """Non-fused version of `normalize_batch_in_training`.
2096 
2097   Arguments:
2098       x: Input tensor or variable.
2099       gamma: Tensor by which to scale the input.
2100       beta: Tensor with which to center the input.
2101       reduction_axes: iterable of integers,
2102           axes over which to normalize.
2103       epsilon: Fuzz factor.
2104 
2105   Returns:
2106       A tuple length of 3, `(normalized_tensor, mean, variance)`.
2107   """
2108   mean, var = nn.moments(x, reduction_axes, None, None, False)
2109   normed = nn.batch_normalization(x, mean, var, beta, gamma, epsilon)
2110   return normed, mean, var
2111 
2112 
2113 def _broadcast_normalize_batch_in_training(x,
2114                                            gamma,
2115                                            beta,
2116                                            reduction_axes,
2117                                            epsilon=1e-3):
2118   """Non-fused, broadcast version of `normalize_batch_in_training`.
2119 
2120   Arguments:
2121       x: Input tensor or variable.
2122       gamma: Tensor by which to scale the input.
2123       beta: Tensor with which to center the input.
2124       reduction_axes: iterable of integers,
2125           axes over which to normalize.
2126       epsilon: Fuzz factor.
2127 
2128   Returns:
2129       A tuple length of 3, `(normalized_tensor, mean, variance)`.
2130   """
2131   mean, var = nn.moments(x, reduction_axes, None, None, False)
2132   target_shape = []
2133   for axis in range(ndim(x)):
2134     if axis in reduction_axes:
2135       target_shape.append(1)
2136     else:
2137       target_shape.append(array_ops.shape(x)[axis])
2138   target_shape = array_ops.stack(target_shape)
2139 
2140   broadcast_mean = array_ops.reshape(mean, target_shape)
2141   broadcast_var = array_ops.reshape(var, target_shape)
2142   if gamma is None:
2143     broadcast_gamma = None
2144   else:
2145     broadcast_gamma = array_ops.reshape(gamma, target_shape)
2146   if beta is None:
2147     broadcast_beta = None
2148   else:
2149     broadcast_beta = array_ops.reshape(beta, target_shape)
2150 
2151   normed = nn.batch_normalization(x, broadcast_mean, broadcast_var,
2152                                   broadcast_beta, broadcast_gamma, epsilon)
2153   return normed, mean, var

2156 def _fused_normalize_batch_in_training(x,
2157                                        gamma,
2158                                        beta,
2159                                        reduction_axes,
2160                                        epsilon=1e-3):
2161   """Fused version of `normalize_batch_in_training`.
2162 
2163   Arguments:
2164       x: Input tensor or variable.
2165       gamma: Tensor by which to scale the input.
2166       beta: Tensor with which to center the input.
2167       reduction_axes: iterable of integers,
2168           axes over which to normalize.
2169       epsilon: Fuzz factor.
2170 
2171   Returns:
2172       A tuple length of 3, `(normalized_tensor, mean, variance)`.
2173   """
2174   if list(reduction_axes) == [0, 1, 2]:
2175     normalization_axis = 3
2176     tf_data_format = 'NHWC'
2177   else:
2178     normalization_axis = 1
2179     tf_data_format = 'NCHW'
2180 
2181   if gamma is None:
2182     gamma = constant_op.constant(
2183         1.0, dtype=x.dtype, shape=[x.shape[normalization_axis]])
2184   if beta is None:
2185     beta = constant_op.constant(
2186         0.0, dtype=x.dtype, shape=[x.shape[normalization_axis]])
2187 
2188   return nn.fused_batch_norm(
2189       x, gamma, beta, epsilon=epsilon, data_format=tf_data_format)

2192 @tf_export('keras.backend.normalize_batch_in_training')
2193 def normalize_batch_in_training(x, gamma, beta, reduction_axes, epsilon=1e-3):
2194   """Computes mean and std for batch then apply batch_normalization on batch.
2195 
2196   Arguments:
2197       x: Input tensor or variable.
2198       gamma: Tensor by which to scale the input.
2199       beta: Tensor with which to center the input.
2200       reduction_axes: iterable of integers,
2201           axes over which to normalize.
2202       epsilon: Fuzz factor.
2203 
2204   Returns:
2205       A tuple length of 3, `(normalized_tensor, mean, variance)`.
2206   """
2207   if ndim(x) == 4 and list(reduction_axes) in [[0, 1, 2], [0, 2, 3]]:
2208     if not _has_nchw_support() and list(reduction_axes) == [0, 2, 3]:
2209       return _broadcast_normalize_batch_in_training(
2210           x, gamma, beta, reduction_axes, epsilon=epsilon)
2211     return _fused_normalize_batch_in_training(
2212         x, gamma, beta, reduction_axes, epsilon=epsilon)
2213   else:
2214     if sorted(reduction_axes) == list(range(ndim(x)))[:-1]:
2215       return _regular_normalize_batch_in_training(
2216           x, gamma, beta, reduction_axes, epsilon=epsilon)
2217     else:
2218       return _broadcast_normalize_batch_in_training(
2219           x, gamma, beta, reduction_axes, epsilon=epsilon)

2299 @tf_export('keras.backend.resize_images')
2300 def resize_images(x, height_factor, width_factor, data_format):
2301   """Resizes the images contained in a 4D tensor.
2302 
2303   Arguments:
2304       x: Tensor or variable to resize.
2305       height_factor: Positive integer.
2306       width_factor: Positive integer.
2307       data_format: One of `"channels_first"`, `"channels_last"`.
2308 
2309   Returns:
2310       A tensor.
2311 
2312   Raises:
2313       ValueError: if `data_format` is neither
2314           `channels_last` or `channels_first`.
2315   """
2316   if data_format == 'channels_first':
2317     original_shape = int_shape(x)
2318     new_shape = array_ops.shape(x)[2:]
2319     new_shape *= constant_op.constant(
2320         np.array([height_factor, width_factor]).astype('int32'))
2321     x = permute_dimensions(x, [0, 2, 3, 1])
2322     x = image_ops.resize_nearest_neighbor(x, new_shape)
2323     x = permute_dimensions(x, [0, 3, 1, 2])
2324     x.set_shape((None, None, original_shape[2] * height_factor
2325                  if original_shape[2] is not None else None,
2326                  original_shape[3] * width_factor
2327                  if original_shape[3] is not None else None))
2328     return x
2329   elif data_format == 'channels_last':
2330     original_shape = int_shape(x)
2331     new_shape = array_ops.shape(x)[1:3]
2332     new_shape *= constant_op.constant(
2333         np.array([height_factor, width_factor]).astype('int32'))
2334     x = image_ops.resize_nearest_neighbor(x, new_shape)
2335     x.set_shape((None, original_shape[1] * height_factor
2336                  if original_shape[1] is not None else None,
2337                  original_shape[2] * width_factor
2338                  if original_shape[2] is not None else None, None))
2339     return x
2340   else:
2341     raise ValueError('Invalid data_format: ' + str(data_format))

2344 @tf_export('keras.backend.resize_volumes')
2345 def resize_volumes(x, depth_factor, height_factor, width_factor, data_format):
2346   """Resizes the volume contained in a 5D tensor.
2347 
2348   Arguments:
2349       x: Tensor or variable to resize.
2350       depth_factor: Positive integer.
2351       height_factor: Positive integer.
2352       width_factor: Positive integer.
2353       data_format: One of `"channels_first"`, `"channels_last"`.
2354 
2355   Returns:
2356       A tensor.
2357 
2358   Raises:
2359       ValueError: if `data_format` is neither
2360           `channels_last` or `channels_first`.

2362   if data_format == 'channels_first':
2363     output = repeat_elements(x, depth_factor, axis=2)
2364     output = repeat_elements(output, height_factor, axis=3)
2365     output = repeat_elements(output, width_factor, axis=4)

2367   elif data_format == 'channels_last':
2368     output = repeat_elements(x, depth_factor, axis=1)
2369     output = repeat_elements(output, height_factor, axis=2)
2370     output = repeat_elements(output, width_factor, axis=3)
2371     return output
2372   else:
2373     raise ValueError('Invalid data_format: ' + str(data_format))

2376 @tf_export('keras.backend.repeat_elements')
2377 def repeat_elements(x, rep, axis):
2378   """Repeats the elements of a tensor along an axis, like `np.repeat`.
2379 
2380   If `x` has shape `(s1, s2, s3)` and `axis` is `1`, the output
2381   will have shape `(s1, s2 * rep, s3)`.
2382 
2383   Arguments:
2384       x: Tensor or variable.
2385       rep: Python integer, number of times to repeat.
2386       axis: Axis along which to repeat.
2387 
2388   Returns:
2389       A tensor.
2390   """
2391   x_shape = x.shape.as_list()
2392   # For static axis
2393   if x_shape[axis] is not None:
2394     # slices along the repeat axis
2395     splits = array_ops.split(value=x,
2396                              num_or_size_splits=x_shape[axis],
2397                              axis=axis)
2398     # repeat each slice the given number of reps
2399     x_rep = [s for s in splits for _ in range(rep)]
2400     return concatenate(x_rep, axis)
2401 
2402   # Here we use tf.tile to mimic behavior of np.repeat so that
2403   # we can handle dynamic shapes (that include None).
2404   # To do that, we need an auxiliary axis to repeat elements along
2405   # it and then merge them along the desired axis.
2406 
2407   # Repeating
2408   auxiliary_axis = axis + 1
2409   x_shape = array_ops.shape(x)
2410   x_rep = array_ops.expand_dims(x, axis=auxiliary_axis)
2411   reps = np.ones(len(x.shape) + 1)
2412   reps[auxiliary_axis] = rep
2413   x_rep = array_ops.tile(x_rep, reps)
2414 
2415   # Merging
2416   reps = np.delete(reps, auxiliary_axis)
2417   reps[axis] = rep
2418   reps = array_ops.constant(reps, dtype='int32')
2419   x_shape *= reps
2420   x_rep = array_ops.reshape(x_rep, x_shape)
2421 
2422   # Fix shape representation
2423   x_shape = x.shape.as_list()
2424   x_rep.set_shape(x_shape)
2425   x_rep._keras_shape = tuple(x_shape)
2426   return x_rep
2427

2449 @tf_export('keras.backend.arange')
2450 def arange(start, stop=None, step=1, dtype='int32'):
2451   """Creates a 1D tensor containing a sequence of integers.
2452 
2453   The function arguments use the same convention as
2454   Theano's arange: if only one argument is provided,
2455   it is in fact the "stop" argument and "start" is 0.

2457   The default type of the returned tensor is `'int32'` to

2459

2465 
2466   Returns:
2467       An integer tensor.
2468 
2469   """
2470   # Match the behavior of numpy and Theano by returning an empty sequence.
2471   if stop is None and start < 0:
2472     start = 0
2473   result = math_ops.range(start, limit=stop, delta=step, name='arange')
2474   if dtype != 'int32':
2475     result = cast(result, dtype)
2476   return result

2814 class Function(object):
2815   """Runs a computation graph.
2816 
2817   It's possible to pass arguments to `tf.Session.run()` via `session_kwargs`.
2818   In particular additional operations via `fetches` argument and additional
2819   tensor substitutions via `feed_dict` arguments. Note that given
2820   substitutions are merged with substitutions from `inputs`. Even though
2821   `feed_dict` is passed once in the constructor (called in `model.compile()`)
2822   we can modify the values in the dictionary. Through this feed_dict we can
2823   provide additional substitutions besides Keras inputs.
2824 
2825   Arguments:
2826       inputs: Feed placeholders to the computation graph.
2827       outputs: Output tensors to fetch.
2828       updates: Additional update ops to be run at function call.
2829       name: A name to help users identify what this function does.
2830       session_kwargs: Arguments to `tf.Session.run()`:
2831                       `fetches`, `feed_dict`, `options`, `run_metadata`.
2832   """
2833 
2834   def __init__(self, inputs, outputs, updates=None, name=None,
2835                **session_kwargs):
2836     updates = updates or []
2837     if not isinstance(inputs, (list, tuple)):
2838       raise TypeError('`inputs` to a TensorFlow backend function '
2839                       'should be a list or tuple.')
2840     if not isinstance(outputs, (list, tuple)):
2841       raise TypeError('`outputs` of a TensorFlow backend function '
2842                       'should be a list or tuple.')
2843     if not isinstance(updates, (list, tuple)):
2844       raise TypeError('`updates` in a TensorFlow backend function '
2845                       'should be a list or tuple.')
2846     self.inputs = list(inputs)
2847     self.outputs = list(outputs)
2848     with ops.control_dependencies(self.outputs):
2849       updates_ops = []
2850       for update in updates:
2851         if isinstance(update, tuple):
2852           p, new_p = update
2853           updates_ops.append(state_ops.assign(p, new_p))
2854         else:
2855           # assumed already an op
2856           updates_ops.append(update)
2857       self.updates_op = control_flow_ops.group(*updates_ops)
2858     self.name = name
2859     # additional tensor substitutions
2860     self.feed_dict = session_kwargs.pop('feed_dict', None)
2861     # additional operations
2862     self.fetches = session_kwargs.pop('fetches', [])
2863     if not isinstance(self.fetches, list):
2864       self.fetches = [self.fetches]
2865     self.run_options = session_kwargs.pop('options', None)
2866     self.run_metadata = session_kwargs.pop('run_metadata', None)
2867     # The main use case of `fetches` being passed to a model is the ability
2868     # to run custom updates
2869     # This requires us to wrap fetches in `identity` ops.
2870     self.fetches = [array_ops.identity(x) for x in self.fetches]
2871     self.session_kwargs = session_kwargs
2872     # This mapping keeps track of the function that should receive the
2873     # output from a fetch in `fetches`: { fetch: function(fetch_output) }
2874     # A Callback can use this to register a function with access to the
2875     # output values for a fetch it added.
2876     self.fetch_callbacks = dict()
2877 
2878     if session_kwargs:
2879       raise ValueError('Some keys in session_kwargs are not supported at this '
2880                        'time: %s', session_kwargs.keys())
2881 
2882     self._callable_fn = None
2883     self._feed_arrays = None
2884     self._feed_symbols = None
2885     self._symbol_vals = None
2886     self._fetches = None
2887     self._session = None
2888 
2889   def _make_callable(self, feed_arrays, feed_symbols, symbol_vals, session):
2890     """Generates a callable that runs the graph.
2891 
2892     Arguments:
2893       feed_arrays: List of input tensors to be fed Numpy arrays at runtime.
2894       feed_symbols: List of input tensors to be fed symbolic tensors at runtime.
2895       symbol_vals: List of symbolic tensors to be fed to `feed_symbols`.
2896       session: Session to use to generate the callable.
2897 
2898     Returns:
2899       Function that runs the graph according to the above options.
2900     """
2901     # Prepare callable options.
2902     callable_opts = config_pb2.CallableOptions()
2903     # Handle external-data feed.
2904     for x in feed_arrays:
2905       callable_opts.feed.append(x.name)
2906     if self.feed_dict:
2907       for key in sorted(self.feed_dict.keys()):
2908         callable_opts.feed.append(key.name)
2909     # Handle symbolic feed.
2910     for x, y in zip(feed_symbols, symbol_vals):
2911       connection = callable_opts.tensor_connection.add()
2912       if x.dtype != y.dtype:
2913         y = math_ops.cast(y, dtype=x.dtype)
2914       from_tensor = ops._as_graph_element(y)
2915       if from_tensor is None:
2916         from_tensor = y
2917       connection.from_tensor = from_tensor.name  # Data tensor
2918       connection.to_tensor = x.name  # Placeholder
2919     # Handle fetches.
2920     for x in self.outputs + self.fetches:
2921       callable_opts.fetch.append(x.name)
2922     # Handle updates.
2923     callable_opts.target.append(self.updates_op.name)
2924     # Handle run_options.
2925     if self.run_options:
2926       callable_opts.run_options.CopyFrom(self.run_options)
2927     # Create callable.
2928     callable_fn = session._make_callable_from_options(callable_opts)
2929     # Cache parameters corresponding to the generated callable, so that
2930     # we can detect future mismatches and refresh the callable.
2931     self._callable_fn = callable_fn
2932     self._feed_arrays = feed_arrays
2933     self._feed_symbols = feed_symbols
2934     self._symbol_vals = symbol_vals
2935     self._fetches = list(self.fetches)
2936     self._session = session
2937 
2938   def _call_fetch_callbacks(self, fetches_output):
2939     for fetch, output in zip(self._fetches, fetches_output):
2940       if fetch in self.fetch_callbacks:
2941         self.fetch_callbacks[fetch](output)
2942 
2943   def __call__(self, inputs):
2944     if not isinstance(inputs, (list, tuple)):
2945       raise TypeError('`inputs` should be a list or tuple.')
2946 
2947     session = get_session()
2948     feed_arrays = []
2949     array_vals = []
2950     feed_symbols = []
2951     symbol_vals = []
2952     for tensor, value in zip(self.inputs, inputs):
2953       if value is None:
2954         continue
2955       if is_sparse(tensor):
2956         sparse_coo = value.tocoo()
2957         indices = np.concatenate((np.expand_dims(sparse_coo.row, 1),
2958                                   np.expand_dims(sparse_coo.col, 1)), 1)
2959         value = (indices, sparse_coo.data, sparse_coo.shape)
2960       if tensor_util.is_tensor(value):
2961         # Case: feeding symbolic tensor.
2962         feed_symbols.append(tensor)
2963         symbol_vals.append(value)
2964       else:
2965         # Case: feeding Numpy array.
2966         feed_arrays.append(tensor)
2967         # We need to do array conversion and type casting at this level, since
2968         # `callable_fn` only supports exact matches.
2969         tensor_type = dtypes_module.as_dtype(tensor.dtype)
2970         array_vals.append(np.asarray(value,
2971                                      dtype=tensor_type.as_numpy_dtype))
2972 
2973     if self.feed_dict:
2974       for key in sorted(self.feed_dict.keys()):
2975         array_vals.append(
2976             np.asarray(self.feed_dict[key], dtype=key.dtype.base_dtype.name))
2977 
2978     # Refresh callable if anything has changed.
2979     if (self._callable_fn is None or feed_arrays != self._feed_arrays or
2980         symbol_vals != self._symbol_vals or
2981         feed_symbols != self._feed_symbols or self.fetches != self._fetches or
2982         session != self._session):
2983       self._make_callable(feed_arrays, feed_symbols, symbol_vals, session)
2984 
2985     fetched = self._callable_fn(*array_vals,
2986                                 run_metadata=self.run_metadata)
2987     self._call_fetch_callbacks(fetched[-len(self._fetches):])
2988     return fetched[:len(self.outputs)]
2989

3053 @tf_export('keras.backend.rnn')
3054 def rnn(step_function,
3055         inputs,
3056         initial_states,
3057         go_backwards=False,
3058         mask=None,
3059         constants=None,
3060         unroll=False,
3061         input_length=None):
3062   """Iterates over the time dimension of a tensor.
3063 
3064   Arguments:
3065       step_function: RNN step function.
3066           Args;
3067               input; Tensor with shape `(samples, ...)` (no time dimension),
3068                   representing input for the batch of samples at a certain
3069                   time step.
3070               states; List of tensors.
3071           Returns;
3072               output; Tensor with shape `(samples, output_dim)`
3073                   (no time dimension).
3074               new_states; List of tensors, same length and shapes
3075                   as 'states'. The first state in the list must be the
3076                   output tensor at the previous timestep.
3077       inputs: Tensor of temporal data of shape `(samples, time, ...)`
3078           (at least 3D).
3079       initial_states: Tensor with shape `(samples, output_dim)`
3080           (no time dimension),
3081           containing the initial values for the states used in
3082           the step function.
3083       go_backwards: Boolean. If True, do the iteration over the time
3084           dimension in reverse order and return the reversed sequence.
3085       mask: Binary tensor with shape `(samples, time, 1)`,
3086           with a zero for every element that is masked.
3087       constants: List of constant values passed at each step.
3088       unroll: Whether to unroll the RNN or to use a symbolic `while_loop`.
3089       input_length: If specified, assume time dimension is of this length.
3090 
3091   Returns:
3092       A tuple, `(last_output, outputs, new_states)`.
3093           last_output: the latest output of the rnn, of shape `(samples, ...)`
3094           outputs: tensor with shape `(samples, time, ...)` where each
3095               entry `outputs[s, t]` is the output of the step function
3096               at time `t` for sample `s`.
3097           new_states: list of tensors, latest states returned by
3098               the step function, of shape `(samples, ...)`.
3099 
3100   Raises:
3101       ValueError: if input dimension is less than 3.
3102       ValueError: if `unroll` is `True` but input timestep is not a fixed
3103       number.
3104       ValueError: if `mask` is provided (not `None`) but states is not provided
3105           (`len(states)` == 0).
3106   """
3107   ndim = len(inputs.shape)
3108   if ndim < 3:
3109     raise ValueError('Input should be at least 3D.')
3110   inputs_shape = inputs.shape
3111   axes = [1, 0] + list(range(2, ndim))
3112   inputs = array_ops.transpose(inputs, (axes))
3113 
3114   if mask is not None:
3115     if mask.dtype != dtypes_module.bool:
3116       mask = math_ops.cast(mask, dtypes_module.bool)
3117     if len(mask.shape) == ndim - 1:
3118       mask = expand_dims(mask)
3119     mask = array_ops.transpose(mask, axes)
3120 
3121   if constants is None:
3122     constants = []
3123 
3124   global uses_learning_phase  # pylint: disable=global-variable-undefined
3125   uses_learning_phase = False
3126 
3127   if unroll:
3128     if not inputs.shape[0]:
3129       raise ValueError('Unrolling requires a fixed number of timesteps.')
3130     states = initial_states
3131     successive_states = []
3132     successive_outputs = []
3133 
3134     input_list = array_ops.unstack(inputs)
3135     if go_backwards:
3136       input_list.reverse()
3137 
3138     if mask is not None:
3139       mask_list = array_ops.unstack(mask)
3140       if go_backwards:
3141         mask_list.reverse()
3142 
3143       for inp, mask_t in zip(input_list, mask_list):
3144         output, new_states = step_function(inp, states + constants)
3145         if getattr(output, '_uses_learning_phase', False):
3146           uses_learning_phase = True
3147 
3148         # tf.where needs its condition tensor
3149         # to be the same shape as its two
3150         # result tensors, but in our case
3151         # the condition (mask) tensor is
3152         # (nsamples, 1), and A and B are (nsamples, ndimensions).
3153         # So we need to
3154         # broadcast the mask to match the shape of A and B.
3155         # That's what the tile call does,
3156         # it just repeats the mask along its second dimension
3157         # n times.
3158         tiled_mask_t = array_ops.tile(mask_t,
3159                                       array_ops.stack(
3160                                           [1, array_ops.shape(output)[1]]))
3161 
3162         if not successive_outputs:
3163           prev_output = zeros_like(output)
3164         else:
3165           prev_output = successive_outputs[-1]
3166 
3167         output = array_ops.where(tiled_mask_t, output, prev_output)
3168 
3169         return_states = []
3170         for state, new_state in zip(states, new_states):
3171           # (see earlier comment for tile explanation)
3172           tiled_mask_t = array_ops.tile(mask_t,
3173                                         array_ops.stack(
3174                                             [1,
3175                                              array_ops.shape(new_state)[1]]))
3176           return_states.append(array_ops.where(tiled_mask_t, new_state, state))
3177         states = return_states
3178         successive_outputs.append(output)
3179         successive_states.append(states)
3180       last_output = successive_outputs[-1]
3181       new_states = successive_states[-1]
3182       outputs = array_ops.stack(successive_outputs)
3183     else:
3184       for inp in input_list:
3185         output, states = step_function(inp, states + constants)
3186         if getattr(output, '_uses_learning_phase', False):
3187           uses_learning_phase = True
3188         successive_outputs.append(output)
3189         successive_states.append(states)
3190       last_output = successive_outputs[-1]
3191       new_states = successive_states[-1]
3192       outputs = array_ops.stack(successive_outputs)
3193 
3194   else:
3195     if go_backwards:
3196       inputs = reverse(inputs, 0)
3197 
3198     states = tuple(initial_states)
3199 
3200     time_steps = array_ops.shape(inputs)[0]
3201     outputs, _ = step_function(inputs[0], initial_states + constants)
3202     output_ta = tensor_array_ops.TensorArray(
3203         dtype=outputs.dtype, size=time_steps, tensor_array_name='output_ta')
3204     input_ta = tensor_array_ops.TensorArray(
3205         dtype=inputs.dtype, size=time_steps, tensor_array_name='input_ta')
3206     input_ta = input_ta.unstack(inputs)
3207     time = constant_op.constant(0, dtype='int32', name='time')
3208 
3209     if mask is not None:
3210       if not states:
3211         raise ValueError('No initial states provided! '
3212                          'When using masking in an RNN, you should '
3213                          'provide initial states '
3214                          '(and your step function should return '
3215                          'as its first state at time `t` '
3216                          'the output at time `t-1`).')
3217       if go_backwards:
3218         mask = reverse(mask, 0)
3219 
3220       mask_ta = tensor_array_ops.TensorArray(
3221           dtype=dtypes_module.bool,
3222           size=time_steps,
3223           tensor_array_name='mask_ta')
3224       mask_ta = mask_ta.unstack(mask)
3225 
3226       def _step(time, output_ta_t, *states):
3227         """RNN step function.
3228 
3229         Arguments:
3230             time: Current timestep value.
3231             output_ta_t: TensorArray.
3232             *states: List of states.
3233 
3234         Returns:
3235             Tuple: `(time + 1,output_ta_t) + tuple(new_states)`
3236         """
3237         current_input = input_ta.read(time)
3238         mask_t = mask_ta.read(time)
3239         output, new_states = step_function(current_input,
3240                                            tuple(states) + tuple(constants))
3241         if getattr(output, '_uses_learning_phase', False):
3242           global uses_learning_phase  # pylint: disable=global-variable-undefined
3243           uses_learning_phase = True
3244         for state, new_state in zip(states, new_states):
3245           new_state.set_shape(state.shape)
3246         tiled_mask_t = array_ops.tile(mask_t,
3247                                       array_ops.stack(
3248                                           [1, array_ops.shape(output)[1]]))
3249         output = array_ops.where(tiled_mask_t, output, states[0])
3250 
3251         masked_states = []
3252         for i in range(len(states)):
3253           states_dim = array_ops.shape(new_states[i])[1]
3254           stacked_states_dim = array_ops.stack([1, states_dim])
3255           tiled_mask = array_ops.tile(mask_t, stacked_states_dim)
3256           masked_state = array_ops.where(tiled_mask, new_states[i], states[i])
3257           masked_states.append(masked_state)
3258         new_states = masked_states
3259 
3260         output_ta_t = output_ta_t.write(time, output)
3261         return (time + 1, output_ta_t) + tuple(new_states)
3262     else:
3263 
3264       def _step(time, output_ta_t, *states):
3265         """RNN step function.
3266 
3267         Arguments:
3268             time: Current timestep value.
3269             output_ta_t: TensorArray.
3270             *states: List of states.
3271 
3272         Returns:
3273             Tuple: `(time + 1,output_ta_t) + tuple(new_states)`
3274         """
3275         current_input = input_ta.read(time)
3276         output, new_states = step_function(current_input,
3277                                            tuple(states) + tuple(constants))
3278         if getattr(output, '_uses_learning_phase', False):
3279           global uses_learning_phase  # pylint: disable=global-variable-undefined
3280           uses_learning_phase = True
3281         for state, new_state in zip(states, new_states):
3282           new_state.set_shape(state.shape)
3283         output_ta_t = output_ta_t.write(time, output)
3284         return (time + 1, output_ta_t) + tuple(new_states)
3285 
3286     final_outputs = control_flow_ops.while_loop(
3287         cond=lambda time, *_: time < time_steps,
3288         body=_step,
3289         loop_vars=(time, output_ta) + states,
3290         maximum_iterations=input_length,
3291         parallel_iterations=32,
3292         swap_memory=True)
3293     last_time = final_outputs[0]
3294     output_ta = final_outputs[1]
3295     new_states = final_outputs[2:]
3296 
3297     outputs = output_ta.stack()
3298     last_output = output_ta.read(last_time - 1)
3299 
3300   axes = [1, 0] + list(range(2, len(outputs.shape)))
3301   outputs = array_ops.transpose(outputs, axes)
3302 
3303   # Static shape inference: (samples, time, ...)
3304   outputs_shape = outputs.shape.as_list()
3305   outputs_shape[0] = inputs_shape[0]
3306   outputs_shape[1] = inputs_shape[1]
3307   outputs.set_shape(outputs_shape)
3308 
3309   if not context.executing_eagerly():
3310     last_output._uses_learning_phase = uses_learning_phase
3311   return last_output, outputs, new_states
3312

3314 @tf_export('keras.backend.switch')
3315 def switch(condition, then_expression, else_expression):
3316   """Switches between two operations depending on a scalar value.
3317 
3318   Note that both `then_expression` and `else_expression`
3319   should be symbolic tensors of the *same shape*.
3320 
3321   Arguments:
3322       condition: tensor (`int` or `bool`).
3323       then_expression: either a tensor, or a callable that returns a tensor.
3324       else_expression: either a tensor, or a callable that returns a tensor.
3325 
3326   Returns:
3327       The selected tensor.
3328 
3329   Raises:
3330       ValueError: If rank of `condition` is greater than rank of expressions.
3331   """
3332   if condition.dtype != dtypes_module.bool:
3333     condition = math_ops.cast(condition, 'bool')
3334   cond_ndim = ndim(condition)
3335   if not cond_ndim:
3336     if not callable(then_expression):
3337 
3338       def then_expression_fn():
3339         return then_expression
3340     else:
3341       then_expression_fn = then_expression
3342     if not callable(else_expression):
3343 
3344       def else_expression_fn():
3345         return else_expression
3346     else:
3347       else_expression_fn = else_expression
3348     x = control_flow_ops.cond(condition, then_expression_fn, else_expression_fn)
3349   else:
3350     # tf.where needs its condition tensor
3351     # to be the same shape as its two
3352     # result tensors
3353     if callable(then_expression):
3354       then_expression = then_expression()
3355     if callable(else_expression):
3356       else_expression = else_expression()
3357     expr_ndim = ndim(then_expression)
3358     if cond_ndim > expr_ndim:
3359       raise ValueError('Rank of `condition` should be less than or'
3360                        ' equal to rank of `then_expression` and '
3361                        '`else_expression`. ndim(condition)=' + str(cond_ndim) +
3362                        ', ndim(then_expression)'
3363                        '=' + str(expr_ndim))
3364     if cond_ndim > 1:
3365       ndim_diff = expr_ndim - cond_ndim
3366       cond_shape = array_ops.concat(
3367           [array_ops.shape(condition), [1] * ndim_diff], axis=0)
3368       condition = array_ops.reshape(condition, cond_shape)
3369       expr_shape = array_ops.shape(then_expression)
3370       shape_diff = expr_shape - cond_shape
3371       tile_shape = array_ops.where(shape_diff > 0, expr_shape,
3372                                    array_ops.ones_like(expr_shape))
3373       condition = array_ops.tile(condition, tile_shape)
3374     x = array_ops.where(condition, then_expression, else_expression)
3375   return x

3378 @tf_export('keras.backend.in_train_phase')

3383 
3384   Arguments:

3405       return x()
3406     else:
3407       return x

3446 @tf_export('keras.backend.relu')
3447 def relu(x, alpha=0., max_value=None, threshold=0):
3448   """Rectified linear unit.
3449 
3450   With default values, it returns element-wise `max(x, 0)`.
3451 
3452   Otherwise, it follows:
3453   `f(x) = max_value` for `x >= max_value`,
3454   `f(x) = x` for `threshold <= x < max_value`,
3455   `f(x) = alpha * (x - threshold)` otherwise.
3456 
3457   Arguments:
3458       x: A tensor or variable.
3459       alpha: A scalar, slope of negative section (default=`0.`).
3460       max_value: float. Saturation threshold.
3461       threshold: float. Threshold value for thresholded activation.
3462 
3463   Returns:
3464       A tensor.
3465   """
3466 
3467   if alpha != 0.:
3468     if max_value is None and threshold == 0:
3469       return nn.leaky_relu(x, alpha=alpha)
3470 
3471     if threshold != 0:
3472       negative_part = nn.relu(-x + threshold)
3473     else:
3474       negative_part = nn.relu(-x)
3475 
3476   clip_max = max_value is not None
3477 
3478   if threshold != 0:
3479     # computes x for x > threshold else 0
3480     x = x * math_ops.cast(math_ops.greater(x, threshold), floatx())
3481   elif max_value == 6:
3482     # if no threshold, then can use nn.relu6 native TF op for performance
3483     x = nn.relu6(x)
3484     clip_max = False
3485   else:
3486     x = nn.relu(x)
3487 
3488   if clip_max:
3489     max_value = _to_tensor(max_value, x.dtype.base_dtype)
3490     zero = _to_tensor(0., x.dtype.base_dtype)
3491     x = clip_ops.clip_by_value(x, zero, max_value)
3492 
3493   if alpha != 0.:
3494     alpha = _to_tensor(alpha, x.dtype.base_dtype)
3495     x -= alpha * negative_part
3496   return x
3497

3500 def elu(x, alpha=1.):
3501   """Exponential linear unit.
3502 
3503   Arguments:
3504       x: A tensor or variable to compute the activation function for.
3505       alpha: A scalar, slope of negative section.
3506 
3507   Returns:

3509   """
3510   res = nn.elu(x)

3558 @tf_export('keras.backend.categorical_crossentropy')
3559 def categorical_crossentropy(target, output, from_logits=False, axis=-1):
3560   """Categorical crossentropy between an output tensor and a target tensor.
3561 
3562   Arguments:
3563       target: A tensor of the same shape as `output`.
3564       output: A tensor resulting from a softmax
3565           (unless `from_logits` is True, in which
3566           case `output` is expected to be the logits).
3567       from_logits: Boolean, whether `output` is the
3568           result of a softmax, or is a tensor of logits.
3569       axis: Int specifying the channels axis. `axis=-1` corresponds to data
3570           format `channels_last', and `axis=1` corresponds to data format
3571           `channels_first`.
3572 
3573   Returns:
3574       Output tensor.
3575 
3576   Raises:
3577       ValueError: if `axis` is neither -1 nor one of the axes of `output`.
3578   """
3579   rank = len(output.shape)
3580   axis = axis % rank
3581   # Note: nn.softmax_cross_entropy_with_logits_v2
3582   # expects logits, Keras expects probabilities.
3583   if not from_logits:
3584     # scale preds so that the class probas of each sample sum to 1
3585     output = output / math_ops.reduce_sum(output, axis, True)
3586     # manual computation of crossentropy
3587     epsilon_ = _to_tensor(epsilon(), output.dtype.base_dtype)
3588     output = clip_ops.clip_by_value(output, epsilon_, 1. - epsilon_)
3589     return -math_ops.reduce_sum(target * math_ops.log(output), axis)
3590   else:
3591     return nn.softmax_cross_entropy_with_logits_v2(labels=target, logits=output)
3592

3594 @tf_export('keras.backend.sparse_categorical_crossentropy')
3595 def sparse_categorical_crossentropy(target, output, from_logits=False, axis=-1):
3596   """Categorical crossentropy with integer targets.
3597 
3598   Arguments:
3599       target: An integer tensor.
3600       output: A tensor resulting from a softmax
3601           (unless `from_logits` is True, in which
3602           case `output` is expected to be the logits).
3603       from_logits: Boolean, whether `output` is the
3604           result of a softmax, or is a tensor of logits.
3605       axis: Int specifying the channels axis. `axis=-1` corresponds to data
3606           format `channels_last', and `axis=1` corresponds to data format
3607           `channels_first`.
3608 
3609   Returns:
3610       Output tensor.
3611 
3612   Raises:
3613       ValueError: if `axis` is neither -1 nor one of the axes of `output`.
3614   """
3615   rank = len(output.shape)
3616   axis = axis % rank
3617   if axis != rank - 1:
3618     permutation = list(range(axis)) + list(range(axis + 1, rank)) + [axis]
3619     output = array_ops.transpose(output, perm=permutation)
3620 
3621   # Note: nn.sparse_softmax_cross_entropy_with_logits
3622   # expects logits, Keras expects probabilities.
3623   if not from_logits:
3624     epsilon_ = _to_tensor(epsilon(), output.dtype.base_dtype)
3625     output = clip_ops.clip_by_value(output, epsilon_, 1 - epsilon_)
3626     output = math_ops.log(output)
3627 
3628   output_shape = output.shape
3629   targets = cast(flatten(target), 'int64')
3630   logits = array_ops.reshape(output, [-1, int(output_shape[-1])])
3631   res = nn.sparse_softmax_cross_entropy_with_logits(
3632       labels=targets, logits=logits)
3633   if len(output_shape) >= 3:
3634     # If our output includes timesteps or spatial dimensions we need to reshape
3635     return array_ops.reshape(res, array_ops.shape(output)[:-1])
3636   else:
3637     return res

3640 @tf_export('keras.backend.binary_crossentropy')
3641 def binary_crossentropy(target, output, from_logits=False):
3642   """Binary crossentropy between an output tensor and a target tensor.
3643 
3644   Arguments:
3645       target: A tensor with the same shape as `output`.
3646       output: A tensor.
3647       from_logits: Whether `output` is expected to be a logits tensor.
3648           By default, we consider that `output`

3677 @tf_export('keras.backend.hard_sigmoid')
3678 def hard_sigmoid(x):
3679   """Segment-wise linear approximation of sigmoid.
3680 
3681   Faster than sigmoid.

3768 def _preprocess_conv1d_input(x, data_format):
3769   """Transpose and cast the input before the conv1d.

3774 
3775   Returns:
3776       A tensor.
3777   """
3778   tf_data_format = 'NWC'  # to pass TF Conv2dNative operations
3779   if data_format == 'channels_first':
3780     if not _has_nchw_support():
3781       x = array_ops.transpose(x, (0, 2, 1))  # NCW -> NWC
3782     else:
3783       tf_data_format = 'NCW'
3784   return x, tf_data_format

3825 def _preprocess_padding(padding):

3846 @tf_export('keras.backend.conv1d')
3847 def conv1d(x,
3848            kernel,
3849            strides=1,
3850            padding='valid',
3851            data_format=None,
3852            dilation_rate=1):
3853   """1D convolution.
3854 
3855   Arguments:
3856       x: Tensor or variable.
3857       kernel: kernel tensor.
3858       strides: stride integer.
3859       padding: string, `"same"`, `"causal"` or `"valid"`.
3860       data_format: string, one of "channels_last", "channels_first".
3861       dilation_rate: integer dilate rate.
3862 
3863   Returns:
3864       A tensor, result of 1D convolution.
3865 
3866   Raises:
3867       ValueError: if `data_format` is neither `channels_last` or
3868       `channels_first`.
3869   """
3870   if data_format is None:
3871     data_format = image_data_format()
3872   if data_format not in {'channels_first', 'channels_last'}:
3873     raise ValueError('Unknown data_format: ' + str(data_format))
3874 
3875   kernel_shape = kernel.shape.as_list()
3876   if padding == 'causal':
3877     # causal (dilated) convolution:
3878     left_pad = dilation_rate * (kernel_shape[0] - 1)
3879     x = temporal_padding(x, (left_pad, 0))
3880     padding = 'valid'
3881   padding = _preprocess_padding(padding)
3882 
3883   x, tf_data_format = _preprocess_conv1d_input(x, data_format)
3884   x = nn.convolution(
3885       input=x,
3886       filter=kernel,

4384 def local_conv(inputs,
4385                kernel,
4386                kernel_size,
4387                strides,
4388                output_shape,
4389                data_format=None):
4390   """Apply N-D convolution with un-shared weights.
4391 
4392   Arguments:
4393       inputs: (N+2)-D tensor with shape
4394           (batch_size, channels_in, d_in1, ..., d_inN)
4395           if data_format='channels_first', or
4396           (batch_size, d_in1, ..., d_inN, channels_in)
4397           if data_format='channels_last'.
4398       kernel: the unshared weight for N-D convolution,
4399           with shape (output_items, feature_dim, channels_out), where
4400           feature_dim = np.prod(kernel_size) * channels_in,
4401           output_items = np.prod(output_shape).
4402       kernel_size: a tuple of N integers, specifying the
4403           spatial dimensions of the N-D convolution window.
4404       strides: a tuple of N integers, specifying the strides
4405           of the convolution along the spatial dimensions.
4406       output_shape: a tuple of (d_out1, ..., d_outN) specifying the spatial
4407           dimensionality of the output.
4408       data_format: string, "channels_first" or "channels_last".
4409 
4410   Returns:
4411       An (N+2)-D tensor with shape:
4412       (batch_size, channels_out) + output_shape
4413       if data_format='channels_first', or:
4414       (batch_size,) + output_shape + (channels_out,)
4415       if data_format='channels_last'.
4416 
4417   Raises:
4418       ValueError: if `data_format` is neither
4419       `channels_last` nor `channels_first`.
4420   """
4421   if data_format is None:
4422     data_format = image_data_format()
4423   if data_format not in {'channels_first', 'channels_last'}:
4424     raise ValueError('Unknown data_format: ' + str(data_format))
4425 
4426   kernel_shape = int_shape(kernel)
4427   feature_dim = kernel_shape[1]
4428   channels_out = kernel_shape[-1]
4429   ndims = len(output_shape)
4430   spatial_dimensions = list(range(ndims))
4431 
4432   xs = []
4433   output_axes_ticks = [range(axis_max) for axis_max in output_shape]
4434   for position in itertools.product(*output_axes_ticks):
4435     slices = [slice(None)]
4436 
4437     if data_format == 'channels_first':
4438       slices.append(slice(None))
4439 
4440     slices.extend([slice(position[d] * strides[d],
4441                          position[d] * strides[d] + kernel_size[d])
4442                    for d in spatial_dimensions])
4443 
4444     if data_format == 'channels_last':
4445       slices.append(slice(None))
4446 
4447     xs.append(reshape(inputs[slices], (1, -1, feature_dim)))
4448 
4449   x_aggregate = concatenate(xs, axis=0)
4450   output = batch_dot(x_aggregate, kernel)
4451   output = reshape(output, output_shape + (-1, channels_out))
4452 
4453   if data_format == 'channels_first':
4454     permutation = [ndims, ndims + 1] + spatial_dimensions
4455   else:
4456     permutation = [ndims] + spatial_dimensions + [ndims + 1]
4457 
4458   return permute_dimensions(output, permutation)

4483       (batch_size, filters, output_length)
4484       if data_format='channels_last'.

4506           if data_format='channels_first'

4508           (batch_size, new_rows, new_cols, filters)
4509           if data_format='channels_last'.
4510       kernel: the unshared weight for convolution,
4511           with shape (output_items, feature_dim, filters).
4512       kernel_size: a tuple of 2 integers, specifying the
4513           width and height of the 2D convolution window.
4514       strides: a tuple of 2 integers, specifying the strides
4515           of the convolution along the width and height.
4516       output_shape: a tuple with (output_row, output_col).
4517       data_format: the data format, channels_first or channels_last.
4518 
4519   Returns:
4520       A 4D tensor with shape:
4521       (batch_size, filters, new_rows, new_cols)
4522       if data_format='channels_first'
4523       or 4D tensor with shape:
4524       (batch_size, new_rows, new_cols, filters)
4525       if data_format='channels_last'.
4526   """
4527   return local_conv(inputs,
4528                     kernel,
4529                     kernel_size,
4530                     strides,
4531                     output_shape,
4532                     data_format)

4535 @tf_export('keras.backend.bias_add')
4536 def bias_add(x, bias, data_format=None):
4537   """Adds a bias vector to a tensor.
4538 
4539   Arguments:
4540       x: Tensor or variable.
4541       bias: Bias tensor to add.
4542       data_format: string, `"channels_last"` or `"channels_first"`.
4543 
4544   Returns:
4545       Output tensor.
4546 
4547   Raises:
4548       ValueError: In one of the two cases below:
4549                   1. invalid `data_format` argument.
4550                   2. invalid bias shape.
4551                      the bias should be either a vector or
4552                      a tensor with ndim(x) - 1 dimension
4553   """
4554   if data_format is None:
4555     data_format = image_data_format()
4556   if data_format not in {'channels_first', 'channels_last'}:
4557     raise ValueError('Unknown data_format: ' + str(data_format))
4558   bias_shape = int_shape(bias)
4559   if len(bias_shape) != 1 and len(bias_shape) != ndim(x) - 1:
4560     raise ValueError(
4561         'Unexpected bias dimensions %d, expect to be 1 or %d dimensions' %
4562         (len(bias_shape), ndim(x)))
4563   # pylint: disable=g-no-augmented-assignment
4564   if ndim(x) == 5:
4565     if data_format == 'channels_first':
4566       if len(bias_shape) == 1:
4567         x = x + reshape(bias, (1, bias_shape[0], 1, 1, 1))
4568       else:
4569         x = x + reshape(bias, (1, bias_shape[3]) + bias_shape[:3])
4570     elif data_format == 'channels_last':
4571       if len(bias_shape) == 1:
4572         x = x + reshape(bias, (1, 1, 1, bias_shape[0]))
4573       else:
4574         x = x + reshape(bias, (1,) + bias_shape)
4575   elif ndim(x) == 4:
4576     if data_format == 'channels_first':
4577       if len(bias_shape) == 1:
4578         if _has_nchw_support():
4579           x = nn.bias_add(x, bias, data_format='NCHW')
4580         else:
4581           x = x + reshape(bias, (1, bias_shape[0], 1, 1))
4582       else:
4583         x = x + reshape(bias, (1, bias_shape[2]) + bias_shape[:2])
4584     elif data_format == 'channels_last':
4585       if len(bias_shape) == 1:
4586         x = nn.bias_add(x, bias, data_format='NHWC')
4587       else:
4588         x = x + reshape(bias, (1,) + bias_shape)
4589   elif ndim(x) == 3:
4590     if data_format == 'channels_first':
4591       if len(bias_shape) == 1:
4592         x = x + reshape(bias, (1, bias_shape[0], 1))
4593       else:
4594         x = x + reshape(bias, (1, bias_shape[1], bias_shape[0]))
4595     elif data_format == 'channels_last':
4596       if len(bias_shape) == 1:
4597         x = x + reshape(bias, (1, 1, bias_shape[0]))
4598       else:
4599         x = x + reshape(bias, (1,) + bias_shape)
4600   else:
4601     x = nn.bias_add(x, bias)
4602   # pylint: enable=g-no-augmented-assignment
4603   return x

4705 # CTC
4706 # TensorFlow has a native implementation, but it uses sparse tensors
4707 # and therefore requires a wrapper for Keras. The functions below convert
4708 # dense to sparse tensors and also wraps up the beam search code that is
4709 # in TensorFlow's CTC implementation
4710 
4711 
4712 @tf_export('keras.backend.ctc_label_dense_to_sparse')
4713 def ctc_label_dense_to_sparse(labels, label_lengths):
4714   """Converts CTC labels from dense to sparse.
4715 
4716   Arguments:
4717       labels: dense CTC labels.
4718       label_lengths: length of the labels.
4719 
4720   Returns:
4721       A sparse tensor representation of the labels.
4722   """
4723   label_shape = array_ops.shape(labels)
4724   num_batches_tns = array_ops.stack([label_shape[0]])
4725   max_num_labels_tns = array_ops.stack([label_shape[1]])
4726 
4727   def range_less_than(_, current_input):
4728     return array_ops.expand_dims(
4729         math_ops.range(label_shape[1]), 0) < array_ops.fill(
4730             max_num_labels_tns, current_input)
4731 
4732   init = math_ops.cast(
4733       array_ops.fill([1, label_shape[1]], 0), dtypes_module.bool)
4734   dense_mask = functional_ops.scan(
4735       range_less_than, label_lengths, initializer=init, parallel_iterations=1)
4736   dense_mask = dense_mask[:, 0, :]
4737 
4738   label_array = array_ops.reshape(
4739       array_ops.tile(math_ops.range(0, label_shape[1]), num_batches_tns),
4740       label_shape)
4741   label_ind = array_ops.boolean_mask(label_array, dense_mask)
4742 
4743   batch_array = array_ops.transpose(
4744       array_ops.reshape(
4745           array_ops.tile(math_ops.range(0, label_shape[0]), max_num_labels_tns),
4746           reverse(label_shape, 0)))
4747   batch_ind = array_ops.boolean_mask(batch_array, dense_mask)
4748   indices = array_ops.transpose(
4749       array_ops.reshape(concatenate([batch_ind, label_ind], axis=0), [2, -1]))
4750 
4751   vals_sparse = array_ops.gather_nd(labels, indices)
4752 
4753   return sparse_tensor.SparseTensor(
4754       math_ops.to_int64(indices), vals_sparse, math_ops.to_int64(label_shape))

4757 @tf_export('keras.backend.ctc_batch_cost')
4758 def ctc_batch_cost(y_true, y_pred, input_length, label_length):
4759   """Runs CTC loss algorithm on each batch element.
4760 
4761   Arguments:
4762       y_true: tensor `(samples, max_string_length)`
4763           containing the truth labels.
4764       y_pred: tensor `(samples, time_steps, num_categories)`
4765           containing the prediction, or output of the softmax.
4766       input_length: tensor `(samples, 1)` containing the sequence length for
4767           each batch item in `y_pred`.
4768       label_length: tensor `(samples, 1)` containing the sequence length for
4769           each batch item in `y_true`.
4770 
4771   Returns:
4772       Tensor with shape (samples,1) containing the
4773           CTC loss of each element.
4774   """
4775   label_length = math_ops.to_int32(array_ops.squeeze(label_length, axis=-1))
4776   input_length = math_ops.to_int32(array_ops.squeeze(input_length, axis=-1))
4777   sparse_labels = math_ops.to_int32(
4778       ctc_label_dense_to_sparse(y_true, label_length))
4779 
4780   y_pred = math_ops.log(array_ops.transpose(y_pred, perm=[1, 0, 2]) + epsilon())
4781 
4782   return array_ops.expand_dims(
4783       ctc.ctc_loss(
4784           inputs=y_pred, labels=sparse_labels, sequence_length=input_length), 1)

4787 @tf_export('keras.backend.ctc_decode')
4788 def ctc_decode(y_pred, input_length, greedy=True, beam_width=100, top_paths=1):
4789   """Decodes the output of a softmax.
4790 
4791   Can use either greedy search (also known as best path)
4792   or a constrained dictionary search.
4793 
4794   Arguments:
4795       y_pred: tensor `(samples, time_steps, num_categories)`
4796           containing the prediction, or output of the softmax.
4797       input_length: tensor `(samples, )` containing the sequence length for
4798           each batch item in `y_pred`.
4799       greedy: perform much faster best-path search if `true`.
4800           This does not use a dictionary.
4801       beam_width: if `greedy` is `false`: a beam search decoder will be used
4802           with a beam of this width.
4803       top_paths: if `greedy` is `false`,
4804           how many of the most probable paths will be returned.
4805 
4806   Returns:
4807       Tuple:
4808           List: if `greedy` is `true`, returns a list of one element that
4809               contains the decoded sequence.
4810               If `false`, returns the `top_paths` most probable
4811               decoded sequences.
4812               Important: blank labels are returned as `-1`.
4813           Tensor `(top_paths, )` that contains
4814               the log probability of each decoded sequence.
4815   """
4816   y_pred = math_ops.log(array_ops.transpose(y_pred, perm=[1, 0, 2]) + epsilon())
4817   input_length = math_ops.to_int32(input_length)
4818 
4819   if greedy:
4820     (decoded, log_prob) = ctc.ctc_greedy_decoder(
4821         inputs=y_pred, sequence_length=input_length)
4822   else:
4823     (decoded, log_prob) = ctc.ctc_beam_search_decoder(
4824         inputs=y_pred,
4825         sequence_length=input_length,
4826         beam_width=beam_width,
4827         top_paths=top_paths)
4828   decoded_dense = [
4829       sparse_ops.sparse_to_dense(
4830           st.indices, st.dense_shape, st.values, default_value=-1)
4831       for st in decoded
4832   ]
4833   return (decoded_dense, log_prob)
